	<article id="post-5674" class="post-5674 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-best-practices tag-digital-first-represents tag-page-design tag-snd">
				<header class="entry-header">
		<h2 class="entry-category-title">
			<a href="../../../../category/best-practices/index.html" title="View all posts in Best Practices" rel="category tag">Best Practices</a></h2>
						<h1 class="entry-title">Advice for page designers: Collaborate, articulate and scare your boss</h1>
					</header><!-- .entry-header -->

				<div class="entry-content">
						<img width="624" height="513" src="../../../../content/uploads/2013/12/176532236-624x513.jpg" class="attachment-post-thumbnail wp-post-image" alt="High wire act: Innovative page design can be like walking a tight rope. It takes time, collaboration, innovation and good relationships to balance it all out. (Thinkstock)" title="Advice for page designers: Collaborate, articulate and scare your boss" />			<div id="thunderdome-caption">High wire act: Innovative page design can be like walking a tight rope. It takes time, collaboration, innovation and good relationships to balance it all out. (Thinkstock)</div>						<p><em>Editor’s note: This is the third in a series of reports from two Digital First Media journalists who attended SND through the <a title="Digital First Represents #SND13: And the winner is …" href="../../../10/18/digital-first-represents-snd13-winner/index.html" target="_blank">Digital First Represents</a> program. </em></p>
<p>There was a lot to take in from all the conference sessions and conversations I had <a title="#SNDLOU: Live updates from DFM’s Eileen Faust and Brian Harr" href="../../../11/07/dfm-journalists-report-live-sndlou-workshop/index.html">while at the SND conference last month</a>. There were many takeaways for me; collaboration, innovation — and yes — scaring your boss. Here’s a smattering of what I took away that can help us all focus on enhancing our storytelling:</p>
<h2><strong>Collaborate</strong></h2>
<p>Sometimes we are islands. Working with others and doing it well is key to producing excellent journalism while at the same time putting energy into making others in the newsroom look better.</p>
<p>Many newsrooms already have a good working relationship with other departments. If not, develop a relationship with everyone, including and especially the digital staff. Even if your idea seems like a print-only idea, bring the digital folks into the process early on. And conversely, ask them to bring you into the process early on. It&#8217;s important to anticipate how the web and mobile presence of a project can increase the impact.</p>
<h2><strong>Innovate</strong></h2>
<p>Innovation should be important to every journalist, but it’s easy to get tripped up trying to follow trends. Falling into that can make us forget what we were trying to accomplish in the first place.</p>
<p>Innovate to solve problems, not to show off what you know.</p>
<p>As designers, especially for A1, the front page is still our biggest selling point. It’s a window to the rest of the paper. It all boils down to getting readers to read a story and so design is crucial. Letting design determine our front page content, however, is a concern. No matter how well it’s executed. It’s easy to over-photoshop or over-design. The question comes down to value. Are we helping or hurting the content by adding more to the design? Are we adding value to the content or just designing to be designing?</p>
<p>If you&#8217;re not passionate about your work and what you design, it’s evident to our readers. We need to demand more of ourselves and what we produce. We are in charge of protecting the integrity of our product.</p>
<div id="attachment_5676" style="width: 624px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a href="../../../../content/uploads/2013/12/SND-PIC.jpg"><img class=" wp-image-5676 " alt="Kenney Marlatt (@kenneymarlatt)" src="../../../../content/uploads/2013/12/SND-PIC.jpg" width="614" height="203" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">A panorama of Tim Frank&#8217;s session from SNDLou. (Kenney Marlatt, @kenneymarlatt)</p></div>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h2><b>Scare your boss</b></h2>
<p>By far my favorite session from SND was from <a href="https://twitter.com/tmfrnk" target="_blank">Tim Frank</a> from the Asbury Park Design Studio. He tied together many of the recurring themes from the week. His session was titled “<a href="http://sndlouisville2013.sched.org/event/8d7bcdd091bff184166fd057ccbda8f5#.Up919WRDt2c" target="_blank">If you’re not scaring your boss, you’re not trying hard enough</a>.” Here’s a snapshot:</p>
<p>Quite often innovation in design is an act of subversion. This leads to questions from old-school editors asking, “How come you ran only two stories above the fold?” Or the photo editor questioning the photo edit.</p>
<p>Solving this begins with having it together. It’s not just, “Hey, what can we get away with?” To have the credibility to get away with something new you have to have your act together. Until you’re meeting deadline and things are running smoothly, you can’t ask to do outlandish things.</p>
<p>“There’s a fine line between an innovator and someone who’s just a pain in the butt,” Frank said.</p>
<p>In a different session I heard that handling A1 is often an entry-level position nowadays. While somewhat true, that doesn’t mean we can’t take charge of the page and act as the conductor. Articulate your ideas with fury. “This is the best solution, and I can tell you why!”</p>
<p>When it comes time to pitch something new or surprising, you want to already have a lot of trust built up with the decision makers. Without buy-in and collaboration, some great pages just won&#8217;t happen. Getting the editor and publisher to buy in to moving that ad on the back page so you can do a wrap with a photo around the front and back starts with good relationships.</p>
<p>But you can’t start huge. When you want to make changes, start small. Having established those relationships, then you can move on to scaring the boss.</p>
<h2><strong>Collaborated advice</strong></h2>
<p>Frank pulled together some nuggets of advice from great visual journalists around the world. Here they are in a mashup with some more verbs and stuff:</p>
<p><strong>You have to be able to articulate your ideas</strong>. Don’t present a half-baked design or presentation, let alone a half-baked idea. Before rushing in to your boss, get feedback from your colleague. They might see holes that you didn’t.</p>
<p><strong>Anticipate what your boss would say. And not say</strong>. What the boss will not say might be your next option in case of rejection. If your idea is gunned down, don’t sulk. Quickly find another one. Think that there’s no best idea, only the best solution. If you introduce small changes as a progression toward what you want, things can happen. If you’re confident in your content. You don’t need to have X amount of things above the fold, or a story count, or anything like that &#8230;</p>
<p><strong>Seize the day.</strong> When you don’t have anything to work with that’s when you have the biggest opportunity.</p>
<p><strong>And some one liners, from Frank and others</strong></p>
<blockquote><p>Your brain doesn’t pay attention to boring things.</p>
<p>It doesn’t have to be related to sex or outrageous. Just do amazing design.</p>
<p>Seduce your audience.</p>
<p>Sometimes you make a huge statement with what you don’t do.</p>
<p>You want to be the person that people want to listen to.</p>
<p>Make your arguments about the audience. “That’s a page that people will connect with.” It’s hard to argue against that.</p></blockquote>
